## Button Behaviour

### Authenticate Button

**FR-003**: Authenticate button MUST validate inputs and trigger authentication flow

#### Initial State
- Button enabled when both fields have values (optional enhancement)
- Button always enabled (validate on click) — Recommended
- Background: `#0A0A0A` (black)
- Text: "Authenticate →" with arrow icon
- Cursor: pointer on hover

#### Loading State
- Triggered on: Form submit (after validation passes)
- Button disabled (no double-submit)
- Text replaced with spinner or "Signing in..."
- Spinner: 16-20px, white color, rotating
- Arrow icon hidden during loading
- Minimum display time: 500ms (prevents flash)

#### Success State
- Triggered on: 200 OK response from API
- Optional: Brief green checkmark animation (300ms)
- Redirect to: `/dashboard` or original intended destination
- Toast notification: "Welcome back, {UserName}!"
- Redirect happens within 1 second of success response

#### Error State
- Triggered on: 4XX / 5XX response from API
- Button re-enabled for retry
- Loading spinner replaced with original text
- Error message displayed above form or inline
- Form fields retain values (user doesn't retype)
- Password field: Optionally cleared for security

#### Validation Flow
```
User clicks "Authenticate"
  ↓
Client-side validation (email format, password rules)
  ↓
If invalid: Display errors, stop
  ↓
If valid: Show loading state, disable button
  ↓
POST /api/v1/auth/signin
  ↓
On 200 OK: Redirect to dashboard
On 4XX/5XX: Display error, re-enable button
```

### Forgot Password Link

- Location: Below password field, right-aligned
- Text: "Forgot Password?"
- Style: Link color (`#0066CC` or similar), underlined on hover
- Click action: Navigate to `/forgot-password`
- No form validation triggered
- No state change on current page

### Register Link

- Location: Footer of form card, centered
- Text: "Don't have an account? Register"
- "Register" portion: Link style, clickable
- Click action: Navigate to `/signup` or `/register`
- No form validation triggered

### Google/Microsoft/SSO Buttons (Non-Email/Password)

- Clicking these initiates OAuth/SSO flow (out of scope for this story)
- Should not interfere with email/password flow
- Optionally: Hide or de-emphasize when email/password focused

